@Endnode

@Node "Equip_Weapon_Edit_Hints_Style"
@Title "Equip/Weapon/Edit/Hints on editing a weapon/Style"
@TOC "Equip_Weapon_Edit"
@Prev "Equip_Weapon_Edit_Hints_Skill"
@Next "Equip_Weapon_Edit_Hints_Combat"

  CharGen uses the fighting-system from 'The Complete Fighter's
Handbook' - i.e. it is possible to use different fighting styles
(Weapon & Shield, One Weapon, Two Weapon, Two Hander). Some styles
might not be available due to restrictions on the Weapon (its hard to
use a Bow one-handed), or because of the characters class or height.

@Endnode

@Node "Equip_Weapon_Edit_Hints_Combat"
@Title "Equip/Weapon/Edit/Hints on editing a weapon/Combat"
@TOC "Equip_Weapon_Edit"
@Prev "Equip_Weapon_Edit_Hints_Style"
@Next "Equip_Weapon_Edit_Hints_Att"

  Tells CharGen weather it should treat the weapon as a missile weapon
or a meele weapon. This is useful with weapons such as the dagger.

@Endnode

@Node "Equip_Weapon_Edit_Hints_Att"
@Title "Equip/Weapon/Edit/Hints on editing a weapon/Att"
@TOC "Equip_Weapon_Edit"
@Prev "Equip_Weapon_Edit_Hints_Combat"
@Next "Equip_Weapon_Edit_Hints_Special"

  This is the number of attacks per round the character has with this
weapon. To the right is a number gadget that allows you to increase or
decrease the number of attacks, by entering a positive or negative
number. This is the possible values:

                Nil, 1/4, 1/3, 1/2, 1/1, 3/2, 2/1, 5/2, 
                3/1, 7/2, 4/1, 9/2, 5/1, 5 ½, 6/1

  The rate of fire (ROF) for a weapon specialist using some missile
weapons have been set by me, when I could not find any relevant
information (in the case of the new firearms), or when the information
available didn't make sense. If you disagree with any of my choises
simply change them via @{" Design/Weapon... " LINK "Design_Weapon"}.

Here is a list of the changes:

   · The blowgun has a base ROF of 2/1, but if you specialize you
     get a ROF of 3/2 (according to table 35 in Player Handbook),
     which doesn't make much sense.
   · The hand crossbow has the same ROF progression as 'Other
     (Non-bow) Missiles' in table 35 in Players Handbook.
   · The knife, shuriken, and stilleto has the same ROF
     progression as the dagger.
   · The ROF progression for firearms has been based on the
     weapon's base ROF and the progression shown in table 35 in
     Players Handbook for light and heavy crossbows, thus on
     levels 1-6 the ROF is unchanged, on levels 7-12 it is one
     step higher, and on level 13 and above is it two steps
     higher.

@Endnode

@Node "Equip_Weapon_Edit_Hints_Special"
@Title "Equip/Weapon/Edit/Hints on editing a weapon/Special"
@TOC "Equip_Weapon_Edit"
@Prev "Equip_Weapon_Edit_Hints_Att"
@Next "Equip_Weapon_Edit_Hints_Size"

  This is where CharGen writes special information. This could be the
range of a missile weapon, effects of style specialization, a reminder
of the possibility of extra damage with firearms and so on...

@Endnode

@Node "Equip_Weapon_Edit_Hints_Size"
@Title "Equip/Weapon/Edit/Hints on editing a weapon/A note about size"
@TOC "Equip_Weapon_Edit"
@Prev "Equip_Weapon_Edit_Hints_Special"
@Next "Equip_Weapon_Edit_Hints_Skill"

  The size of a person (which is used for determining which weapons
can be used and how) is now calculated from the person's height and
not from the average racial height, thus a very large (higher than 4'
= medium size) halfling can use a scimitar (also medium size). I have
used the height intervals from Monstrous Compendium:

                Tiny        : up to 2'
                Small       : 2'+ to 4'
                Medium      : 4'+ to 7'
                Large       : 7'+ and up
@Endnode

