@Endnode

@Node "Settings_Character_MaximumHp"
@Title "Settings/Options/This character/Maximum hp on first level"
@TOC "Settings_Character"
@Prev "Settings_Character_Int13"
@Next "Settings_Character_Generous"

  The character gains maximum hit points on first level (i.e. no rolls
are nessesary). Use this option to create tougher characters, if your
campaign is especially 'high-powered'.

@Endnode

@Node "Settings_Character_Generous"
@Title "Settings/Options/This character/Generous hp calculation method"
@TOC "Settings_Character"
@Prev "Settings_Character_MaximumHp"
@Next "Settings_Character_Less"

  This method of calculation hit points for multiclassed characters is
more generous than the one given in PHB. The reason for this is mainly
that the routine rounds up instead of down, and you can add all rolls
before dividing by the number of classes.

  My rule: All hit dice for each level divided by the number of
classes (round up) plus the most advantageous constitution bonus. When
you don't advance simultaneously in all classes you only gain hit
points when your higest class level increases. Example: A 3/3 level
fighter/thief with constitution 17, who advances a level as thief gets
(d6+d10)/2+3 hit points. He gets no hit points when he later advances
to 4'th level as fighter.

@Endnode

@Node "Settings_Character_Less"
@Title "Settings/Options/This character/Less damage on tiny thrown wpn."
@TOC "Settings_Character"
@Prev "Settings_Character_Generous"
@Next "Settings_Character_NoBonus"

  This is a rule I use myself. It does not grant a full damage bonus
for high strength, when the weapon is a very small thrown weapon (such
as a thrown knife). In these cases the program gives you half the
strength damage bonus (rounded down). By selecting this option you can
use this rule.

@Endnode

@Node "Settings_Character_NoBonus"
@Title "Settings/Options/This character/No bonus for strength on bows"
@TOC "Settings_Character"
@Prev "Settings_Character_Less"
@Next "Settings_Character_AC"

  This option dissallows strength bonuses on bow attack roll and
damage. It is an option here, rather than just under @{" Design/Weapon " LINK "Design_Weapon"},
so you can let some characters have heavy pull bows, while not
others.

@Endnode

@Node "Settings_Character_AC"
@Title "Settings/Options/This character/Do not limit AC from -10 to 10"
@TOC "Settings_Character"
@Prev "Settings_Character_NoBonus"
@Next "Settings_Character_Piecemeal"

  CharGen normally limits AC to the 10 to -10 range. If you don't want
these limits imposed, select this option.

@Endnode

@Node "Settings_Character_Piecemeal"
@Title "Settings/Options/This character/Piecemeal armors allowed"
@TOC "Settings_Character"
@Prev "Settings_Character_AC"
@Next "Settings_Character_NoMaxThief"

  Use the Piecemeal armor rules from 'The Complete Fighter's
Handbook'.

@Endnode

@Node "Settings_Character_NoMaxThief"
@Title "Settings/Options/This character/No maximum on thief skills"
@TOC "Settings_Character"
@Prev "Settings_Character_Piecemeal"
@Next "Settings_Character_LongEquipment"

  Normally thief skills cannot exceed 95% (99% for Rangers), but I use
a slightly different rule in my campaign (yes, yet a another rule ;-).

  My rule: A thiefs skill _CAN_ exceed 95%, but if, when the skill is
checked, you roll 96% or above the skill check fails. Now you might
say that there is no practical difference between this rule and the
one in PHB, but there is: If the DM decides to penalize the characters
skill (e.g. because of a difficult lock) the penalty is deducted from
the characters skill before the roll is made. Thus if a thief with
105% skill in an ability gets a -20% penalty he would have a 85%
chance of succeding, whereas a thief under PHB rules (max 95% skill)
would have 75% chance of succeding.

@Endnode

@Node "Settings_Character_LongEquipment"
@Title "Settings/Options/This character/Long equipment lines"
@TOC "Settings_Character"
@Prev "Settings_Character_NoMaxThief"
@Next "Settings_Character_AllAllowed"

